  "prompt": "Does the warranty on the car electrical wiring lapse in case one gets a music system fitted from outside and not from the company showroom?",
  "response": "Typically, the warranty on a car's electrical wiring can be affected if modifications are made, such as installing an aftermarket music system. Most manufacturers may consider such modifications as alterations that could potentially introduce issues not covered under the original warranty. \n\nHere are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Warranty Terms**: Review the specific terms of your vehicle's warranty. Many manufacturers outline what modifications will void the warranty\u2014often including aftermarket installations.\n\n2. **Direct Relation**: If the installation of the aftermarket music system causes a malfunction in the car's electrical system, the manufacturer may refuse warranty coverage for the related electrical issues.\n\n3. **Installation Quality**: If the unit is installed properly and does not interfere with the vehicle's original systems, some dealerships may still honor the warranty for non-related issues.\n\n4. **Manufacturer vs. Dealer Policies**: Manufacturer warranties may differ from dealer policies. Sometimes dealers may have more lenient views on aftermarket modifications.\n\n5. **Consultation**: It\u2019s usually best to consult with your dealership or review the warranty documentation to get a definitive answer regarding the specific impact on your warranty.\n\nIn any case, keeping detailed records of installations and any potential issues may help when dealing with warranty claims.",
